        output='Based on the provided text, here is a clear breakdown of the **Connectivity segment**, its revenue streams, and how they are defined.\n\n### **Connectivity Segment Overview**\nThe Connectivity segment operates **Starlink**, the company\'s global high-speed, low-latency broadband and mobile connectivity service. It delivers services to consumers, enterprises, and governments via its constellation of Low-Earth Orbit (LEO) satellites.\n\n---\n\n### **Revenue Streams & Sub-Segments**\nRevenue within the Connectivity segment is generated from three primary categories:\n\n#### 1. **Consumer Revenue**\n*   **Description:** Subscription fees from individual consumers for Starlink broadband service.\n*   **Sub-segments & Details:**\n    *   **Consumer Broadband:** The core offering providing home internet with "fiber-like download speeds." Revenue is driven by the number of **Starlink Subscribers** and the **Average Revenue Per User (ARPU)**.\n    *   **Revenue Recognition:** Recognized ratably over the monthly subscription term. Revenue is typically composed of:\n        *   A recurring monthly subscription fee based on geographic market and download speed.\n        *   A one-time sale of the **Starlink Kit** (terminal and related equipment).\n*   **Scale:** Consumer subscribers represented **over 60% of Connectivity segment revenue** in 2024.\n\n#### 2. **Enterprise & Government Revenue**\n*   **Description:** Revenue from commercial businesses and public-sector entities.\n*   **Sub-segments & Details:**\n    *   **Enterprise Connectivity:** Services for businesses, including:\n        *   **Aviation**\n        *   **Maritime**\n        *   **Mobility**\n        *   Other enterprise solutions (e.g., remote site connectivity).\n    *   **Government Connectivity (Starshield):** Long-term, secure satellite network contracts for government and national security applications. Revenue is often recognized over time using a **percentage-of-completion** method.\n    *   **Starlink Mobile:** This offering is explicitly included in this category. It provides mobile connectivity services (initially SMS and OTT voice) through partnerships with Mobile Network Operators (MNOs). Revenue is shared with MNO partners based on services included in their customer plans.\n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Contracts are often structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, and capacity, or on a percentage-of-completion basis.\n\n#### 3. **Revenue from MNO Partners (Starlink Mobile)**\n*   **Description:** While part of Enterprise & Government, this stream has a distinct model. The company charges MNOs either a **fixed fee** or a **per-mobile user fee**, which is typically passed through to the end customer via the carrier.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Financial Drivers & Metrics**\n*   **Growth Driver:** Subscriber growth and increased adoption by enterprise and government customers.\n*   **Offsetting Factor:** **ARPU decline**, primarily due to international expansion and the addition of lower-priced service plans.\n*   **Financial Reporting:**\n    *   The segment\'s profitability is measured by **Segment Adjusted EBITDA**.\n    *   **Deferred Revenue** primarily relates to enterprise and government contracts within this segment.\n\n### **Summary Table of Connectivity Revenue Streams**\n\n| Revenue Stream | Description | Key Components & Recognition |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Consumer** | Subscriptions from individual users for Starlink broadband. | - Recurring monthly fee (recognized ratably).<br>- One-time Starlink Kit sale (recognized on delivery/installation). |\n| **Enterprise & Government** | Contracts with businesses and public entities. | - **Enterprise:** Aviation, Maritime, Mobility, etc.<br>- **Government (Starshield):** Long-term secure contracts.<br>- Often uses % of completion or subscription/data models. |\n| **Starlink Mobile** | Mobile connectivity via MNO partnerships. | - Revenue-sharing with ~30 MNO partners.<br>- Included in the **Enterprise & Government** category in financial tables. |\n\nIn essence, the Connectivity segment\'s revenue is built on a consumer subscription base, amplified by large-scale contracts with enterprises and governments, and further extended through mobile carrier partnerships.',
